Photo by Investopedia on August 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Understanding Market Sentiment Market sentiment, or "investor sentiment,' isn't always based on fundamentals, but technical indicators. Market sentiment is about feelings and emotion, whereas fundamental value is about business performance. Contrarians, or investors who tend to trade differently than the majority, rely on market sentiment when making decisions. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Indicators to Measure Market Sentiment The VIX Called the "fear index" and driven by options prices. The High-Low Index An index comparing the stocks making 52-week highs to stocks making 52-week lows. Bullish Percentage Index Measures the number of stocks with bullish patterns based on point and figure charts. Moving Averages Investors use both the 50 and 200 day simple moving average (SMA). Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, screen and text that says 'Real World Example December 2018 After slow corporate earnings and unresolved trade tensions between the United States and China, investors felt bearish about the market. Photo by Investopedia on August 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Infrastructure refers to the physical systems a business, region, or country relies on. These systems tend to require a lot of human capital and investment, but are vital to a nation's economic development. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Understanding Infrastructure The word 'Infrastructure' originates from French, with infra- meaning "below" and structure meaning 'building.' Large- and small-scale organizational frameworks can be applicable to infrastructure as long as there are physical components present. Public financing, control, and regulation is common when dealing with large-scale infrastructure. At smaller scales, private firms or localized monopolies are responsible for projects. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Types of Infrastructure Soft Infrastructure Requires human capital to deliver certain services to population. Hard Infrastructure Types of physical systems that make it necessary to run a modern, industrialized nation. Critical Infrastructure Assets defined as being essential to the function of a society. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Examples of Infrastructure Soft Infrastructure Financial institutions, governmental systems, and education systems. Hard Infrastructure Roads, highways, and bridges. Critical Infrastructure Facilities for shelter and heating, telecommunication, public health, and agriculture. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 11, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What is Happening Right Now? The Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act of 2021 A$1.2 trillion infrastructure package was recently passed by the U.S. Senate. This bill provides funding for roads, bridges, railroads, power grids, and more. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Stagflation refers to a simultaneous increase in inflation an decrease in gross domestic product (GDP). Haln 7.25 It's also characterized by slow economic growth, high unemployment, and rising prices. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Understanding Stagflation Stagflation was long believed to be impossible because widely accepted economic theories from the 19th century ruled out such a model. The Great Depression and emergence of Keynesian economics caused economists to reevaluate inflation and unemployment. Stagflation is an example of how economic data can sometimes conflict with popular theories and policies. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Causes of Stagflation Oil Prices A sudden increase in oil prices reduces a country's economic output. The Gold Standard President Nixon removed the gold standard, removing commodity backing for the U.S. dollar. Poor Economic Policies Strict regulation of markets, goods and labor. Investopedia'.

Photo by Investopedia on August 04, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Why is Stagflation Bad? Slow economic growth should lead to an increase in unemployment, but not an increase in prices. Stagflation contradicts this notion. With rising unemployment and inflation there is a decrease in consumer spending power. There is less money to spend and all money being worth less and less. Investopedia'.
